[{"short_id":"tosnfy","short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tosnfy","created_at":"2024-02-08T11:48:36.000-06:00","title":"Question: How to have file-backed persistent memory","url":"","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eHello lobsters (assuming this is how users here are called)!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eMy idea of a persistent file looks like this: two copies of the data stored in one file, then mapped to memory with \u003ccode\u003emmap\u003c/code\u003e. [version] is an integer.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode\u003e[data] [checksum] [version]\n[data] [checksum] [version]\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTo write data, only write to the older copy (one with smaller [version]).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ecopy [data] from new to old\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003emodify [data]\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ecalculate and write [checksum]\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003ewrite [version] (the current new copyâ€™s [version] + 1)\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\n\u003ccode\u003emsync/fsync\u003c/code\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eNow the older copy is newer.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCan I do better than this under Linux/*BSD or whatever system that supports POSIX API?\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Hello lobsters (assuming this is how users here are called)!\r\n\r\nMy idea of a persistent file looks like this: two copies of the data stored in one file, then mapped to memory with `mmap`. [version] is an integer.\r\n\r\n```\r\n[data] [checksum] [version]\r\n[data] [checksum] [version]\r\n```\r\n\r\nTo write data, only write to the older copy (one with smaller [version]).\r\n\r\n1. copy [data] from new to old\r\n2. modify [data]\r\n3. calculate and write [checksum]\r\n4. write [version] (the current new copy's [version] + 1)\r\n5. `msync/fsync`.\r\n\r\nNow the older copy is newer.\r\n\r\nCan I do better than this under Linux/*BSD or whatever system that supports POSIX API?",